1 (4) The Advisory Council on Autism Spectrum Disorders may invite individuals who
2 are not members to serve on committees and workgroups.
3 (5) Appointed members of the Advisory Council on Autism Spectrum Disorders shall
4 serve without compensation, but shall be reimbursed for actual expenses incurred in
5 the performance of duties in accordance with KRS 45.101 and administrative
6 regulations promulgated thereunder. Members of the council shall initially be
7 appointed to serve staggered terms and thereafter shall be appointed to serve a term
8 of four (4) years.
9 (6) The Cabinet for Health and Family Services, the Personnel Cabinet, the Finance
10 and Administration Cabinet, and the Office of the State Budget Director shall take
11 all necessary actions to effectuate this section.
12 (7) The Advisory Council on Autism Spectrum Disorders shall be responsible for:
13 (a) Promoting the vision for Kentucky's services and supports to persons on the
14 autism spectrum and their families and advocating for improved quality and
15 evidence-based practices for persons on the autism spectrum and their
16 families;
17 (b) Promoting the early screening, identification, early intervention, and
18 appropriate use of evidence-based practices and standards of care for persons
19 on the autism spectrum across the lifespan;
20 (c) Strengthening state, regional, and local level collaboration and coordination
21 with families, self-advocates, support groups, and state agencies to further
22 coordinate, develop, and enhance the service delivery system for persons on
23 the autism spectrum across the lifespan;
24 (d) Gathering and analyzing research and data to assess the quality and
25 availability of programs and services for persons on the autism spectrum and
26 providing recommendations on assessments, interventions, and treatment
27 modalities across the lifespan;
Page 3 of 6
SB006920.100 - 1477 - XXXX 3/25/2026 3:30 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 69/EN
1 (e) Developing recommendations for:
2 1. Increasing participation in existing federal, state, and local programs
3 that serve children, youth, and adults on the autism spectrum;
4 2. Enhancing the current professional development and planning for future
5 workforce development to incorporate research and evidence-based
6 practices;
7 3. Establishing standards of care and undertaking efforts to ensure
8 promotion of these standards statewide; and
9 4. Promoting the development of services and supports to transition youth
10 and adults on the autism spectrum;
11 (f) Assessing the capacity and effectiveness of institutes of higher education in
12 the state toward supporting the development of the workforce for persons on
13 the autism spectrum;
14 (g) Requesting and utilizing federal, state, and private funds, including funds
15 from philanthropic sources;
16 (h) Improving procedures for ensuring accountability and measuring success of
17 programs that receive state, federal, and philanthropic funds;
18 (i) Obtaining reports and issuing progress updates on state and federally funded
19 services that impact the quality of Kentucky's system of care for persons on
20 the autism spectrum;
21 (j) Completing a biennial report with the Office of Autism and submitting it to
22 the Commonwealth Council on Developmental Disabilities, the Governor, and
23 the Legislative Research Commission. The first report shall be due on or
24 before September 30, 2017, and subsequent reports shall be due each
25 September 30 in odd-numbered years thereafter; and
26 (k) Other duties and responsibilities as designated by the Governor.
27 (8) The Advisory Council on Autism Spectrum Disorders shall:
Page 4 of 6
SB006920.100 - 1477 - XXXX 3/25/2026 3:30 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 69/EN
1 (a) Administer and distribute funds from the autism spectrum disorder trust
2 fund created in Section 1 of this Act;
3 (b) Develop a written plan for the use of funds made available under Section 1
4 of this Act. The initial plan shall be completed on or before October 1, 2026,
5 and shall be updated on an annual basis on or before October 1 of each
6 year thereafter. The plan shall at a minimum include the following:
7 1. A summary of existing autism spectrum disorder research, awareness,
8 treatment, and funding programs provided to individuals in Kentucky;
9 2. A needs assessment for individuals with autism spectrum disorder in
10 Kentucky that identifies additional research funding needs by disorder
11 type and geographic area, with support for why the identified
12 programs are needed; and
13 3. A prioritized list of programs and research projects that the advisory
14 council will address with funding available through the competitive
15 grant program established under subsection (9) of this section; and
16 (c) Provide to the Governor and the Legislative Research Commission an
17 annual report by October 1 of each year. The report shall include:
18 1. The plan developed under this subsection for the use of funds for the
19 current and next fiscal year;
20 2. A summary of the use and impact of prior year funds;
21 3. A summary of the activities of the advisory council during the prior
22 fiscal year; and
23 4. Any recommendations for future initiatives or actions regarding
24 autism spectrum disorder research funding.
25 (9) (a) The cabinet shall promulgate administrative regulations in accordance with
26 KRS Chapter 13A to establish a competitive, open grant program to provide
27 funding to nonprofit entities, academic medical centers, and government
Page 5 of 6
SB006920.100 - 1477 - XXXX 3/25/2026 3:30 PM Engrossed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 69/EN
1 agencies offering research funding and services for autism spectrum
2 disorder services to individuals in Kentucky impacted by the disorder.
3 (b) The grant program shall provide funding to research projects and programs
4 in accordance with the priorities established in the plan developed under
5 subsection (8) of this section.
6 (c) The administrative regulations shall at a minimum:
7 1. Establish an application process and requirements;
8 2. Set forth program and outcome measurement requirements;
9 3. Establish an application review and award process; and
10 4. Provide monitoring, oversight, and reporting requirements for funded
11 programs.
12 Section 3. Whereas it is essential that the General Assembly promptly provide
13 access to research and services for autism spectrum disorders in the Commonwealth in
14 order to provide for the health and safety of citizens, an emergency is declared to exist,
15 and this Act takes effect upon its passage and approval by the Governor or upon its
16 otherwise becoming a law.
